## 🏷️ How Content Gets Tagged

The JenniNexus site uses a **multi-source tagging system** that pulls tags from different places:

### **1. YAML Files (Playlists & Videos)**

Location: `public_html/resources/playlists/*.yaml`

**Example** (gaming.yaml):
```yaml
playlists:
  - id: "PL6WnzXOaRqA09bFvNzWaJa3q97w7bGo6c"
    title: "Nintendo Switch Games"
    icon: "nintendo-switch"
    description: "Portable adventures and cozy Switch exclusives"
    tags: ["gaming", "nintendo-switch", "portable", "adventure"]  # ← Tags defined here
```

**These tags automatically:**
- ✅ Populate the offcanvas filter panel on gaming.php
- ✅ Get added to `content_tags.json` by automation scripts
- ✅ Enable filtering via tag buttons
- ✅ Show up in `/tags.php` results

### **2. content_tags.json (Central Registry)**

Location: `public_html/resources/playlists/content_tags.json`

**Purpose:** Central database mapping all content IDs to their tags

**Format:**
```json
{
  "playlist:PL6WnzXOaRqA09bFvNzWaJa3q97w7bGo6c": {
    "title": "Nintendo Switch Games",
    "url": "/gaming.php#playlist-nintendoswitch",
    "tags": ["gaming", "nintendo-switch", "portable", "adventure", "console"]
  },
  "blog:my-gaming-post": {
    "title": "My Gaming Experience",
    "url": "/blog/my-gaming-post.php",
    "tags": ["gaming", "ps5", "review"]
  }
}
```

**Key Format Types:**
- `playlist:{PLAYLIST_ID}` - YouTube playlists
- `blog:{SLUG}` - Blog posts
- `page:{PAGE}` - Static pages
- `game/{SLUG}` - Game project pages
- `video/{VIDEO_ID}` - Individual videos

### **3. Blog Posts (blog-posts.yaml)**

Location: `public_html/resources/playlists/blog-posts.yaml`

**Example:**
```yaml
- slug: pax-west-2022
  title: "PAX West 2022 — Gallery & Recap"
  date: 2022-09-05
  category: gaming
  tags: ["pax-west", "gaming", "community"]  # ← Blog post tags
  excerpt: "My experience at PAX West 2022..."
```

### **4. Page-Level Tags (HTML data attributes)**

Location: PHP files like `gaming.php`, `diy.php`

**Example:**
```html
<div class="content-item" 
     data-category="gaming" 
     data-tags="gaming,nintendo-switch,portable">
  <!-- Content card HTML -->
</div>
```

**Used for:** Client-side JavaScript filtering without page reload

---

## 🔄 Tag Data Flow

Here's how tags flow through the system:

```
1. Developer adds tags to gaming.yaml
   tags: ["gaming", "nintendo-switch", "portable"]
   
2. youtube-grid.js loads gaming.yaml
   ↓
   
3. tag-system.js reads tags.json
   Converts: "nintendo-switch" (slug) → "Nintendo Switch" (display name)
   ↓
   
4. Offcanvas panel shows clickable tags
   User clicks: "Nintendo Switch" + "Indie"
   ↓
   
5. User clicks "Apply Filters"
   Redirects to: /tags.php?filters=Nintendo Switch,Indie
   ↓
   
6. tags.php converts names → slugs
   "Nintendo Switch" → "nintendo-switch"
   "Indie" → "indie"
   ↓
   
7. tags.php loads content_tags.json
   Finds: "playlist:PL..." has tags [31, 39, 10]
   Converts: 31 → "gaming", 39 → "nintendo-switch", 10 → "indie"
   ↓
   
8. Comparison: ["nintendo-switch", "indie"] ∩ ["gaming", "nintendo-switch", "indie"] = MATCH
   ↓
   
9. Display: Playlist card shown with tag badges "Gaming", "Nintendo Switch", "Indie"
```

