## ➕ Adding Tags to Content

### **For YouTube Playlists:**

1. Open the appropriate YAML file:
   - Gaming: `public_html/resources/playlists/gaming.yaml`
   - DIY: `public_html/resources/playlists/diy.yaml`
   - Game Dev: `public_html/resources/playlists/gamedev.yaml`

2. Find your playlist entry:
   ```yaml
   - id: "PL6WnzXOaRqA09bFvNzWaJa3q97w7bGo6c"
     title: "Nintendo Switch Games"
   ```

3. Add or update tags:
   ```yaml
   - id: "PL6WnzXOaRqA09bFvNzWaJa3q97w7bGo6c"
     title: "Nintendo Switch Games"
     tags: ["gaming", "nintendo-switch", "portable", "adventure", "console"]  # ← Add here
   ```

4. **Optional:** Run automation to update `content_tags.json`:
   ```powershell
   .\scripts\fix-tag-system.ps1
   ```
   
   Or just let the JavaScript load tags dynamically from the YAML!

### **For Blog Posts:**

1. Open `public_html/resources/playlists/blog-posts.yaml`

2. Find your blog post entry:
   ```yaml
   - slug: my-post
     title: "My Blog Post"
     date: 2025-11-01
   ```

3. Add tags:
   ```yaml
   - slug: my-post
     title: "My Blog Post"
     date: 2025-11-01
     category: gaming
     tags: ["gaming", "ps5", "review", "fps"]  # ← Add here
   ```

4. Run automation to update `content_tags.json`:
   ```powershell
   .\scripts\fix-tag-system.ps1
   ```

### **For Static Pages:**

Add tags directly in `content_tags.json`:

```json
{
  "page:custom-project": {
    "title": "My Custom Project",
    "url": "/projects/custom.php",
    "tags": ["gamedev", "unity", "indie", "3d-modeling"]
  }
}
```

